ISLR Chapter 7

Nonlinear Models

Here we explore the use of nonlinear models using some tools in R.

require(ISLR)
## Loading required package: ISLR
attach(Wage)

Polynomials

First we will use polynomials, and focus on a single predictor age:

fit=lm(wage~poly(age,4), data=Wage)
summary(fit)

The poly() function generates a basis of orthogonal polynomials. Lets make a plot of the fitted function, along with the standard error of the fit.

We specify the with and height of the figure as below:

agelims=range(age)
age.grid=seq(from=agelims[1],to=agelims[2])               # min to max
preds=predict(fit,newdata=list(age=age.grid), se=TRUE)
se.bands=cbind(preds$fit+2*preds$se,preds$fit-2*preds$se)
plot(age, wage, col='darkgrey')
lines(age.grid,preds$fit, lwd=2, col='blue')     # default lwd = 1 (line width)
matlines(age.grid, se.bands, col='blue', lty=2)  # lty=2 = broken line

There are other more direct ways of doing this in R. For example below we fit a polynomial directly.

fita=lm(wage~age+I(age^2)+I(age^3)+I(age^4), data=Wage)
summary(fita)

Here I() is a wrapper function; we need it because age^2 means something to the formula language, while I(age^2) is protected. The coefficients are different to those we got before! This is because the basis is different in each model. Need to review what the basis means here.However, the fits are the same.

plot(fitted(fit), fitted(fita))

By using orthogonal polynomials in this simle way, it turns out that we can separately test for each coefficient. So if we look at the summary again, we can see that the linear, quadratic and cubic terms are significant, but not the quartic.

This only works with linear regression, and if there is a single predictor. In general we would use anova() as this next example illustrates. Output of Anova tells us that age is needed in the model. So too is age^2, but age^3 is marginal (significant at 5% level only).

fita=lm(wage~education, data=Wage)
fitb=lm(wage~education+age, data=Wage)
fitc=lm(wage~education+poly(age,2),data=Wage)
fitd=lm(wage~education+poly(age,3), data=Wage)
anova(fita, fitb, fitc, fitd)
## Analysis of Variance Table

Polynomial logistic regression

Now we fit a logistic regression model to a binary response variable constructed from wage. We code the big earners (>250k) as 1, else 0.

fit=glm(I(wage>250) ~ poly(age,3), data=Wage, family=binomial)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = I(wage > 250) ~ poly(age, 3), family = binomial, 
##     data = Wage)

##               Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)

preds=predict(fit, list(age=age.grid),se=T)
se.bands=preds$fit + cbind(fit=0, lower=-2*preds$se, upper=2*preds$se)
se.bands[1:5,]
##         fit      lower     upper
## 1 -7.664756 -10.759826 -4.569686
## 2 -7.324776 -10.106699 -4.542852

## 4 -6.695229  -8.917158 -4.473300
## 5 -6.404868  -8.378691 -4.431045

We have done the computations on the logit scale. To transform we need to apply the inverse logit mapping. \[p=\frac{e^\eta}{1+e^\eta}.\] (Here we have used the ability of MarkDown to interpret TeX expressions). We do this simultaneously for all three columns of se.bands: (note that we divide by 10 so that the high earner appear in the plot!)

prob.bands=exp(se.bands)/(1+exp(se.bands))
matplot(age.grid, prob.bands, col='blue', lwd=c(2,1,1), lty=c(1,2,2),type='l',ylim=c(0,.1))
points(jitter(age), I(wage>250)/10, pch='l', cex=0.5)
